      "type": "edit",
      "id": "84340a36a64ca15e",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "84340a36a64ca15e",
        "text": "One can define the term decision premise very broadly and include everything that is taken for granted in a decision. However, this would make the term superfluous. A useful restriction might be to allow only decisions to be considered decision premises for purposes of organization theory. Then the term would coincide with that of uncertainty absorption and include all, even quite concrete, prior decisions - for example, that an expenditure that is ordered will be made, or that a completed matter will be decreed \"on file.\" Understood in this way, decision premises are the result of absorbed uncertainty or, in other words, the form in which the organization remembers uncertainty absorption. The term becomes fruitful only through a further (and at the same time paradoxical) qualification: there are decisions that establish decision premises for an as yet undetermined multitude of other decisions.  In such cases, the scope of decisions is extended by restriction; or as said before: complexity is created by reduction."
      },
